"The image displays a diagram explaining the meaning of the numbers and letters on a tire size specification. The tire size indicated is "P215/60R16 94H". Below this specification, there are seven numbered arrows pointing to specific parts of the tire code:  1. The first arrow with the number "1" points to the letter "P", which stands for Passenger vehicle type. 2. The second arrow, number "2", points to "215", which refers to the nominal width of the tire in millimeters. 3. Arrow number "3" points to "60", indicating the aspect ratio of the tire (the height of the sidewall as a percentage of the tire's width). 4. The fourth arrow, number "4", points to the letter "R", which means the tire has Radial construction. 5. Arrow number "5" indicates the number "16", which is the wheel diameter in inches that the tire is intended to fit. 6. The sixth arrow, number "6", points to "94", which is the load index, relating to the maximum load-carrying capacity of the tire. 7.
